h levels of everyday gender-based and sexual violence. At the same time, both boast long histories of resisting such violence and its location in wider cultures of patriarchy, settler colonialism and class and caste privilege.Through the lens of the #MeToo moment, the book tracks histories of feminist organising in both countries, while also revealing how newer strategies extended or limited these struggles. Intimacy and injury is a timely mapping of a shifting political field around gender-based violence in the global south. In proposing comparative, interdisciplinary, ethnographically rich and analytically astute reflections on #MeToo, it provides new and potentially transformative directions to scholarly debates this book builds transnational feminist knowledge and solidarity in and across the global south.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIntimate partner violence-India. 0aMeToo movement. 0aWomenxViolence againstzIndia. 0aWomenxViolence againstzSouth Africa. 0aWomenzIndiaxSocial conditions. 0aWomenzSouth AfricaxSocial conditions. 0aWomen-India-Social conditions. 0aWomen-Social conditions. 0aWomen-South Africa-Social conditions. 0aWomen-Violence against-India. 0aWomen-Violence against-South Africa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  a#LoSHA.  a#MeToo.  aAffect.  aDigital activism.  aFeminism.  aGender-based violence.  aIndia.  aRape culture.  aSocial movements.  aSouth Africa.1 aArora, Swati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBansode, Rupali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashonga, Ragi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreakey, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Nechama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id